text=:Category: LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild%0a:Essential: {Category.LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild$:essential}%0a:Title: AAVE and Hiring Policies%0a:Author: BenP%0a:Section: E%0a:Completed: 24.04.2021 - 16:05%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a----%0a%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210511-222542-203490#%0a* [-11.05.2021 - 15:25-] || TA_mason marked as complete%0a#foxend 210511-222542-203490#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Comments for student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0aSummary: \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aThis article explores how the hiring process is affected by accent.%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aThis article:%0ahttps://acloserlookataave.wordpress.com/2014/03/05/58/%0a%0aand the associated video linked to it discuss how AAVE accents are viewed and discriminated against by employers looking to hire applicants. A linked expansion on the page details examples like the syllable deletion to go from "about" to "'bout", or the use of the Auxiliary contraction "ain't."%0a%0aIn the video, linguists and other experts explore the line between not hiring someone based on assumptions about the person's intelligence or education based solely on the AAVE accent, and not hiring someone because their accent makes them hard to understand. They delineate between the two by explaining how the first is based on nothing more than mere prejudice against speakers of AAVE or other accents and how the second is based on the practicality of hiring an employee that is incomprehensible due to their accent. In a sense, the difference lies in whether the accent or the preconceived notions about speakers of that accent are the reason someone is not hired. %0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:GradedBy: TA_mason:)
